Pages = {{167-172}},
Note = {{AWRA 2000 Spring Specialty Conference on Water Resources in Extreme
   Environments, AMER WATER RESOURCES ASSOC, ALASKA STATE SECT, ANCHORAGE,
   AK, MAY 01-03, 2000}},
Organization = {{Amer Water Resources Assoc; Univ Alaska Fairbanks Water \& Environm Res
   Ctr; Alaska Power \& Tel Co; BP Explorat; GW Sci; Harza Engn Co;
   Meridian Management Inc; Montgomery Watson; Oasis Environm Inc; Remote
   Utilities Syst Grp}},
Abstract = {{Biogeochemical cycling in the boreal forest landscape is driven by
   physical, chemical and biological properties that are regulated by
   permafrost and the fire disturbance regime. We measured stream
   concentrations of dissolved organic carbon (DOC), and nitrate (NO3-) in
   watersheds underlain by 3\% permafrost, 18\% permafrost, and 53\%
   permafrost during two storm events in July and September 1999. In the
   intermediate permafrost watershed, we examined the effect of the
   FROSTFIRE prescribed burn that took place in July 1999. The storm
   hydrograph for the September event was separated into old and new water
   components using a two-end member mixing model. Post-fire observations
   for storm events in July and September 1999 show positive relationships
   between DOC and discharge for all basins. The increase in DOC during
   storms was greatest in HIP, moderate in the burn, and smallest in LoP.
   The NO3- response was variable across all basins. There was a negative
   relationship between NO3- and discharge in LoP and a positive
   relationship in HiP. Our results show that DOC and NO3- concentrations
   are influenced by permafrost. Nitrate and DOC increased in Hip despite a
   larger contribution of ``new{''} water (precipitation low in NO3- and
   DOG) to the stormflow peak. Nitrate was leached in the active layer of
   HiP, but diluted by rain water or NO3- depleted soil water in LoP. In
   the burn basin, the immediate fire effect is shown by a non-linear
   response of NO3- to increased flow in the post-fire rain event in Jury.
   This hyteresis indicates that nitrate from burned soils in the
   contributing area for stormflow may have reached the stream. The
   long-term effect of the prescribed fire will be driven by changes in the
   active layer depth due to removal of the insulative moss layer on the
   forest floor. Future stormflow analyses will include isotope tracers to
   identify sources of carbon and nitrogen to stream chemistry.}},
