Month = {{APR}},
Abstract = {{This paper analyses the use of Markovian models to describe, predict and
   simulate dynamics of a Quercus coccifera garrigue near Montpellier,
   under four different fire regimes, resulting from combinations of two
   fire frequencies (every 3, and 2 years) and two burning seasons (late
   spring and early autumn) compared to an undisturbed control. Recorded
   data from permanent transects made it possible to estimate transitions
   between the dominant species, and results suggest that post-fire
   succession has the properties of a first-order Markovian process.
   Transition matrices provide important insights on the nature and
   mechanisms of secondary succession. Relative stability of the systems
   under any of the fire regimes considered supports the conclusion that
   most plant species present are fire-adapted regenerating rapidly by
   vegetative means.}},
